nt of Psychiatry, University of Michigan, MI, Ann Arbor, USA</aff><aff id="A4"><label>d</label>Department of Internal Medicine, University of Michigan, MI, Ann Arbor, USA</aff><aff id="A5"><label>e</label>Department of Surgery, University of Michigan, MI, Ann Arbor, USA</aff><aff id="A6"><label>f</label>Department of Neurology, University of Michigan, MI, Ann Arbor, USA</aff><author-notes><corresp id="CR1"><bold>Address Correspondence to:</bold> Anne C. Fernandez, 2800 Plymouth Ave Bldg 16, Ann Arbor MI, 48109, USA, <email>acfernan@umich.edu</email>, Phone: 734-232-0313; Fax: 734-764-7932</corresp></author-notes><pub-date pub-type="ppub"><month>1</month><year>2024</year></pub-date><pub-date pub-type="epub"><day>08</day><month>1</month><year>2024</year></pub-date><volume>48</volume><issue>1</issue><issue-id pub-id-type="pmc-issue-id">453154</issue-id><fpage>153</fpage><lpage>163</lpage><pub-history><event event-type="nihms-submitted"><date><day>08</day><month>11</month><year>2023</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-release"><date><day>08</day><month>01</month><year>2025</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-live"><date><day>08</day><month>01</month><year>2025</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-last-change"><date iso-8601-date="2025-01-08 00:25:15.983"><day>08</day><month>01</month><year>2025</year></date></event></pub-history><self-uri xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" content-type="pmc-pdf" xlink:href="nihms-1942991.pdf"/><abstract id="ABS1"><sec id="S1"><title>Background:</title><p id="P1">Preoperative risky alcohol use is one of the most common surgical risk factors. Accurate and early identification of risky alcohol use could enhance surgical safety. Artificial Intelligence-based approaches such as natural language processing (NLP) provide an innovative approach to identify alcohol-related risks from patients&#8217; electronic health records (EHR) before surgery.</p></sec><sec id="S2"><title>Methods:</title><p id="P2">Clinical notes (n=53,629) from pre-operative patients in a tertiary care facility were analyzed for evidence of risky alcohol use and alcohol use disorder. One hundred of these records were reviewed by experts and labeled for comparison. A rules-based NLP model was built and assessed the clinical notes for the entire population. Additionally, we assessed each record for presence or absence of alcohol-related International Classification of Diseases (ICD) diagnoses codes as an additional comparator.</p></sec><sec id="S3"><title>Results:</title><p id="P3">NLP correctly identified 87% of the human-labeled patients classified with risky alcohol use. In contrast, diagnosis codes alone only correctly identified 29% of these patients. In terms of specificity, NLP correctly identified 84% of the non-risky cohort, while diagnosis codes correctly identified 90% of this cohort. In analysis of the full dataset, the NLP-based approach identified 3 times more patients with risky alcohol use than ICD codes.</p></sec><sec id="S4"><title>Conclusions:</title><p id="P4">NLP, an artificial intelligence-based approach, efficiently and accurately identifies alcohol-related risk in patients&#8217; EHRs. This approach could supplement other alcohol screening tools to identify patients in need of intervention, treatment, and/or postoperative withdrawal prophylaxis. Alcohol-related ICD diagnosis had limited utility relative to NLP, which extracts richer information within clinical notes to classify patients.</p></sec></abstract><kwd-group><kwd>Artificial Intelligence</kwd><kwd>Natural Language Processing</kwd><kwd>Alcohol Drinking</kwd><kwd>Surgery</kwd><kwd>Alcohol Use Disorder</kwd></kwd-group><custom-meta-group><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-qastatus</meta-name><meta-value>0</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-live</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-embargo</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta